<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Profile of FCC Comissioner Ness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NAME -- Susan Ness.  
</P>
<P>
	AGE-BIRTH DATE -- 50, Aug. 11, 1948; Elizabeth, N.J.  
</P>
<P>
	EDUCATION -- B.A. Douglass College (Rutgers University); MBA from  
the Wharton School, University of Pennsylvania; law degree from 
Boston College. 
</P>
<P>
	EXPERIENCE -- Clinton-appointed FCC Commissioner; sworn in May  
23, 1994. Term ends June 30, 1999; Vice President and Group Head of 
the Communications Industries Division of American Security Bank; 
Founder of a project, part of the National Women's Political 
Caucus, which increased the representation of women on the federal 
bench; Served as assistant counsel to the former House Committee on 
Banking, Currency and Housing. 
</P>
<P>
	FAMILY -- Husband, Larry Schneider, an attorney; Two children:  
Elisabeth, 14, David, 10. Father Edward Ness is deceased and was an 
accountant. Mother Ruth was a hairdresser, homemaker and secretary 
and lives in New Jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	MOTTO -- Wishing does not make it so. You've got to make it  
happen yourself. 
</P>
<P>
	AT HOME RULES LIMITING HER CHILDREN TO WATCHING TV, TALKING ON  
PHONE OR USING COMPUTER -- None that are enforceable. 
</P>
<P>
	HEROES -- Mother for her common sense, warmth and love of people;  
daughter for the sense of joy and enthusiasm in what she does; 
Hillary Rodham Clinton for her ability to stay focused on any task 
while never losing sight of her family; Elaine Jones, president of 
NAACP legal defense fund, for lobbying on issues that she believes 
in so thoroughly. 
</P>
<P>
	FIRST TASTE OF COMMUNICATIONS -- Newscaster at college radio  
station. Hosted a weekly program in French, featuring French music. 
Most memorable experience: covering the opening of the 1967 World's 
Fair in Montreal where she rubbed elbows with Walter Cronkite. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
