<DOCNO> APW19990418.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 16:12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Steps Up Air War on Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO today launched its most active  
day of airstrikes in its assault on Yugoslavia, pummeling 
refineries, bridges and dozens of other targets in what it claimed 
were ``highly successful'' operations. But the refugee crisis only 
deepened with ethnic Albanians pouring out of Kosovo at the rate of 
a thousand an hour. In the latest tragedy, a car carrying a family 
across the border to Albania struck a land mine planted by Serb 
forces, killing three children, their mother and their grandmother. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S.: Kosovo Dead May Total 100,000  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tens of thousands of young ethnic Albanian men  
-- possibly as many as 100,000 -- may have been killed by Serb ethnic 
cleansing of Kosovo, the U.S. ambassador for war crimes said today. 
David Scheffer also said Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic 
``certainly (is) a prime target for investigation'' as a war 
criminal. Scheffer, appearing on Fox News, brought side-by-side 
photographs of the town of Izbica that he said proved mass killings 
by Serbs. The photos depicted an area taken at different times. In 
the photo on the right, up to 150 graves had appeared where nothing 
existed before. 

</P>
<P>
	Abortion Foes Open Buffalo Protests  
</P>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Activists on both sides of the abortion  
issue noisily clashed on the steps of a federal courthouse today, 
the first day of a week-long campaign by abortion foes. Protesters 
participating in Operation Save America will denounce abortion, 
child pornography and teen sex. Abortion rights activists have 
condemned the timing and choice of location for the Operation 
Rescue campaign. The demonstrations were announced a week after 
last October's sniper killing of abortion provider Dr. Barnett 
Slepian inside his home in the Buffalo suburb of Amherst. 

</P>
<P>
	Miami-Area Fire Burns 70,000 Acres  
</P>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- A fire burned out of control in the  
Everglades today, consuming 70,000 acres and creating clouds of 
smoke that darkened the Miami area. The fire came within 100 yards 
of Interstate 75, closing the main coast-to-coast route across 
south Florida. The fire began on the Everglades' western edge 
yesterday, possibly ignited by heat from a vehicle's catalytic 
converter. 

</P>
<P>
	Relatives To Mark Oklahoma Bombing  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Relatives of some of the Murrah Federal  
Building bombing victims will gather tomorrow to observe the fourth 
anniversary of the disaster, their last such observance before a 
permanent memorial park is completed next year. A feature of the 
park will be the Survivor Tree, an elm that survived the blast that 
killed 168 people. A museum that is projected to open in 2000, and 
offices for the Memorial Institute for the Prevention of Terrorism 
also will be built. 

</P>
<P>
	N. Irish Militants Urged To Disarm  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Northern Ireland's top  
Protestant politician appealed to the province's major outlawed 
pro-British groups to hand in weapons as the best way to force the 
IRA to do the same. David Trimble, elected last year to lead 
Northern Ireland's still-unformed Protestant-Catholic government, 
made the appeal on the eve of renewed talks in London. Like their 
enemies in the Irish Republican Army, the Ulster Defense 
Association and Ulster Volunteer Force have been observing 
cease-fires but have refused to start disarming. 

</P>
<P>
	Compaq President, CFO Both Resign  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Without notice and with little explanation,  
Compaq Computer Corp. president and CEO Eckhard Pfeiffer resigned 
today. Compaq's chief financial officer also stepped down. The 
company's board formed an interim chief executive's office to 
handle day-to-day operations of the world's largest supplier of 
computer systems. The company has been under tremendous pressure 
from stockholders since an April 9 announcement that its 
first-quarter earnings would be lower than expected. 

</P>
<P>
	'Great' Gretzky Ends NHL Career  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Wayne Gretzky ended his NHL career today to the  
rousing cheers and endless chants from an overflow crowd at Madison 
Square Garden. Gretzky ended his career with an assist, setting up 
a second-period goal as his New York Rangers fell to Pittsburgh 2-1 
in overtime. After the game, Gretzky skated one lap around the rink 
with his teammates in tow, then came an encore, as a lone spotlight 
followed him around the ice and Carly Simon's ``Nobody Does It 
Better'' blared. 

</P>
<P>
	Cubs Edge Brewers 6-5  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Jose Hernandez hit a home run leading off the  
10th inning today, lifting the Chicago Cubs over the Milwaukee 
Brewers 6-5. Sammy Sosa's double set up pinch-hitter Manny 
Alexander's two-out, two-run double in the ninth, giving the Cubs a 
5-3 lead. The Brewers tied it in the bottom half on RBI singles by 
Fernando Vina and Marquis Grissom. Hernandez then connected off 
Valerio De Los Santos (0-1). 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
