<DOCNO> APW19990418.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 09:32:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Concert Promoter Avram Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- Concert promoter Marcel Avram is out of  
prison and back at work, planning two shows on the cusp of the 
millennium for his biggest client, Michael Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	Avram was released this month after serving two years for tax  
evasion. He was quoted by Focus newsmagazine as saying Jackson 
intends to give a concert Dec. 31 in Sydney, Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	``After the show we'll fly to Honolulu and play again on  
December 31, because of the 22-hour time difference,'' he told the 
magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	The Romanian-born Avram, whose client list also has included  
Pink Floyd and Joe Cocker, was convicted in 1997 of dodging tax 
payments of nearly $2.8 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
