<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates Farm Out RF Jose Guillen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Pirates, upset with Jose  
Guillen's attitude and lack of power this season, demoted their 
starting right fielder to Triple-A Nashville on Sunday and didn't 
promise when he would be back. 
</P>
<P>
	The move ostensibly was made to clear roster room so rookie  
pitcher Todd Ritchie could start Sunday in Cincinnati. In reality, 
it signaled the Pirates had run out of patience with their talented 
but moody outfielder. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jose was shocked, probably because he's been here for two  
years now,'' manager Gene Lamont said. ``But I told him he needs to 
go down and start playing like Jose Guillen can play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to onlookers in the Pirates' clubhouse, Guillen was  
visibly upset with the news. Left fielder Al Martin, who regains 
his starting job with the move, pulled Guillen aside and delivered 
a 15-minute pep talk. 
</P>
<P>
	The demotion was surprising in part because it came so early in  
the season. The Pirates anticipated this might be the breakthrough 
year that Guillen drove in more than 100 runs and began hitting for 
more power. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen jumped directly from Class A to the Pirates' starting  
lineup in 1997 at age 20 and drove in 154 runs in his first two 
seasons, including 84 RBIs last year -- second on the club only to 
Kevin Young's 108. 
</P>
<P>
	Guillen, 22, is batting .280, but had no homers, only 4 RBIs and  
just two extra-base hits. Last year, he hit 14 homers and jumped 
his doubles from 20 as a rookie to 38. 
</P>
<P>
	He also made several baserunning blunders, the latest Friday  
when he was tagged out between second and third base on Abraham 
Nunez's two-run single in the fourth inning of a 6-5 loss to the 
Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Jose needs to go down and start swinging the bat  
better,'' Lamont said. ``He's not swinging real bad, but he's not 
really pounding the ball like he can. I hope he goes down and has a 
good attitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates and Guillen had a falling out during spring training  
when Guillen waited until the last minute to apply for an entry 
visa for his new wife. He wound up missing the first two weeks of 
camp and angering the team. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Cam Bonifay was especially critical of Guillen's  
handling of the situation. Guillen, in turn, felt the Pirates 
unfairly blamed him for a complicated problem that wasn't resolved 
until an immigration lawyer and Sen. Rick Santorum intervened. 
</P>
<P>
	``He needs to grow up,'' Bonifay said.  
</P>
<P>
	Bonifay was so upset that he weighed sending Guillen to  
Nashville just before spring training ended. But Lamont interceded, 
saying he wanted Guillen in the lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	Lamont apparently needed only two weeks of the season to change  
his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't really hit the ball like he could (during spring  
training) and he hasn't done it since the season started, either,'' 
Lamont said. ``He's just not swinging the bat the way he can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Guillen out the lineup for now, Brian Giles shifts from  
left field to right field, with Martin playing most of the time in 
left. Freddy Garcia, who had nine homers in 172 at-bats last 
season, also will play some in left. 
</P>
<P>
	``It won't be a strict platoon,'' Lamont said.  
</P>
<P>
	Brant Brown will stay in center field and will start mostly  
against right-handers, with switch hitters Turner Ward and Adrian 
Brown also playing against left-handers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
