<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Dream True' Tells Tale of Friends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Peter Emmons, a beleaguered architect, needs  
space, literally and psychologically. Or so he sings in ``Dream 
True,'' the tale of two boyhood friends who discover they can 
communicate through dreams. 
</P>
<P>
	What Peter needs even more is a better musical, preferably one  
with a coherent story and an accessible score that can tell his 
troubles with a lot more oomph than found in this earnest and 
pretentious show on view at off-Broadway's Vineyard Theater. 
</P>
<P>
	In a glum season for new musicals, ``Dream True'' is one of the  
most muddled, stranding its talented cast and leaving theatergoers 
bewildered. 
</P>
<P>
	Director Tina Landau also provided the book and most of the  
lyrics. She strikes out with all three. ``Dream True,'' apparently 
based on a George du Maurier novel ``Peter Ibbetson,'' has no shape 
or flow. It floats aimlessly like a cloud, scattering its 
performers across the stage in arty poses as it tells a convoluted 
yarn. 
</P>
<P>
	Landau's lyrics rarely rise above the commonplace, not doing  
much to untangle the story or at least make it more interesting. 
</P>
<P>
	Little Peppy (later Peter) and young Verne are best friends back  
in Wyoming in the mid-1940s. But the friendship breaks up after 
Peppy's Uncle Howard spirits the lad back East to New Haven, Conn., 
to get an education. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter goes to Yale, finds a girl (the sober-sided Madge played  
by the sad-eyed Judy Kuhn), becomes an architect in New York, pines 
for Verne and suffers a breakdown. Verne also comes to New York, 
becomes a gay activist, becomes HIV-positive and dies. 
</P>
<P>
	That's an awful lot of plot to get through, but despite all the  
story, no real characters emerge. Not even Peter develops, despite 
the heroic efforts of performer Jeff McCarthy to turn him into a 
credible human being. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarthy has a strong voice and a winning manner, but there is  
little for him to hang the character on. Daniel Jenkins, as the 
sought-after Verne, has even less to work with. 
</P>
<P>
	The score by Ricky Ian Gordon does contain some promising  
musical material. There's a lovely lyrical moment early in the 
first act called ``Finding Home,'' but it is sung by Peter's 
mother, who quickly disappears. At least the song is reprised at 
the end of Act 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The settings by G.W. Mercier and production designs by Jan  
Hartley suggest Georgia O'Keeffe, by way of Magritte. Sort of 
American West meets Belgian surrealism. 
</P>
<P>
	The other-worldly surroundings help produce a distancing effect.  
Maybe ``Dream True'' wants to remove itself from any kind of 
emotional connection with the audience. In that respect, it 
succeeds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
