<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> KJ: No NBA This Season, Maybe Never </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Kevin Johnson says he won't play in the NBA this  
season and probably is finished for good. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, in Phoenix for a ceremony honoring former teammate Tom  
Chambers, said Sunday that he's had plenty of opportunities but 
never found the ideal situation that would have lured him back. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I'm going to play, but I'm not going to rule it  
out until after the summmer,'' Johnson said. ``I'll evaluate it in 
the summer and then make a final determination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson played all 11 of his NBA seasons with the Suns. He is  
the team's career assists leader and No. 3 scorer, but he and the 
franchise parted ways after last season when the Suns decided to go 
with Jason Kidd as the team's undispited floor leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said he never found a situation that seemed good enough  
for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard for me to put on another uniform,'' Johnson said.  
```I knew that all along. I knew when I stepped down from here that 
it would be almost impossible for me to play anywhere else. It 
would take an ideal situation. I told everybody no. Every other 
team in the league called me -- the Lakers right off the bat. But I 
just can't put on another uniform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Johnson said, he misses the NBA.  
</P>
<P>
	``I miss my teammates. I miss the fans. This has been a part of  
my life since I was 13-14 years old. You know, 20 years. There's 
nothing like NBA basketball. That was a great period of my life. 
</P>
<P>
	``To be able to move on and have no regrets and take all the  
good memories with me that I've bottled up, it's great. I don't 
actually feel I made the wrong choice by not playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he's in good enough shape to play right now.  
</P>
<P>
	``My body's better than it's ever been,'' he said. ``I can walk  
up stairs and my body doesn't hurt. I feel great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson might be back at America West Arena someday to have his  
name added to the list that now includes Chambers, Walter Davis, 
Paul Westphal, Alvan Adams, Connie Hawkins and Dick Van Arsdale. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never know,'' he said, ``but I'm too young to be talking  
about that. That's for old guys.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
