<DOCNO> APW19990418.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 16:51:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Collins is Miami's Pick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jimmy Johnson got his man today: Cecil Collins,  
the troubled, talented running back from Louisiana. And the Miami 
Dolphins needed no more than the first choice of the NFL draft's 
fifth round to get him. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the good things about Cecil is he admits he made a lot  
of mistakes, stupid mistakes and wants to put his life back in 
order,'' Johnson said of Collins, who played just five college 
games at LSU and McNeese State before injury and arrest ended his 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got tremendous running ability, can break tackles with  
great speed. He makes things happen every time he touches the 
ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The draft plodded through its second day in the theater at  
Madison Square Garden, even more of a sideshow than usual -- seven 
floors above Wayne Gretzky was ending his hockey career for the New 
York Rangers against the Pittsburgh Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no run on quarterbacks like Saturday, when the first  
three picks overall and five of the first 12 went on the position. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Germaine of Ohio State, whom some draft analysts thought  
might sneak into the first or second round, was chosen with the 
sixth pick of the fourth round by the St. Louis Rams -- the eighth 
QB chosen. Aaron Brooks of Virginia went late in the fourth round 
to Green Bay, and Kevin Daft of Cal-Davis was taken by Tennessee in 
the fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	But no more went until the seventh round, when New England chose  
Michael Bishop, the Kansas State star who might also be used as a 
running back or wide receiver. Chris Greisen of Northwest Missouri, 
taken by Arizona, and Scott Covington of Miami, chosen by 
Cincinnati, went in the seventh round, making it 13 QBs drafted in 
253 picks. 
</P>
<P>
	One player who dropped way down was safety Anthony Poindexter of  
Virginia, who would likely have been a first-round pick had he not 
severely injured his knee last season. He went to Baltimore in the 
seventh and final round. Notre Dame's star running back, Autry 
Denson, also went in the seventh -- to Tampa Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	The last pick, who will be honored at ``Irrelevant Week'' in  
Newport Beach, Calif., was Jim Finn, chosen by Chicago. Finn, a 
running back from Pennsylvania, was in the audience and received a 
loud ovation from the sparse crowd remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now I'm going to camp and prove I'm not Mr. Irrelevant,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The trades continued Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	The draft finished with 26, none bigger than Saturday's  
first-round blockbuster in which New Orleans surrendered its entire 
draft plus first- and third-round choices next year to Washington 
to select running back Ricky Williams with the fifth overall pick. 
The Redskins then dealt some of the acquired picks to Chicago, and 
ended up with cornerback Champ Bailey, the player they wanted 
anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	So New Orleans spent Sunday without a pick, the only time in  
draft history that a team had just one choice. 
</P>
<P>
	That made a Sunday headliner of Collins, who in a deal worked  
out just before the draft pleaded guilty to two misdemeanors and 
two felonies. He got four years probation for breaking into two 
apartments and fondling two young women. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone in the NFL knew Johnson was willing to take a chance on  
him, as he did unsuccessfully with Lawrence Phillips two years ago. 
But nobody was sure when Jimmy would jump at a back who in three 
games at LSU in 1987 ran for 583 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	It turned out to be late enough so that it was practically a  
no-lose situation for the Dolphins, who hope Collins can emulate 
the feats of Minnesota wide receiver Randy Moss, who fell to 21st 
overall last season because of off-field problems and ended up an 
All-Pro and the offensive rookie of the year.. 
</P>
<P>
	``My concern is giving people second chances. If they don't do  
what's right we go on with our business,'' said Johnson, who said 
Collins reminds him of ``a faster Emmitt Smith.'' ``He's a risk. 
That's why we waited until the fifth round. Everyone in the league 
wanted to take him.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
