<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penn Fullback Latest Mr. Irrelevant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- Finding this year's ``Mr. Irrelevant''  
took some doing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to get the last pick in the draft, and get a guy  
from the Ivy League, and find him at the place to draft him,'' Mark 
Hatley, the Chicago Bears' vice president of player personnel, said 
with a laugh. ``That was the toughest thing for us to do in the 
draft, but it's sort of funny how things fall out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bears made Pennsylvania fullback Jim Finn this year's ``Mr.  
Irrelevant,'' the title affectionately given to the last player 
taken in the draft over the last few years. Besides a chance to 
make the Chicago roster, Finn gets a trip to Disneyland and a 
parade as part of an extended series of festivities in his honor. 
</P>
<P>
	Finn was in New York for the pick, which was announced by ``Mr.  
Irrelevant'' founder Paul Salata. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, I'm going to go to camp and prove I'm not `Mr.  
Irrelevant,'' Finn said. 
</P>
<P>
	The last pick of the draft was supposed to go the expansion  
Cleveland Browns, but they traded it to the Bears. Chicago was 
looking for a fullback throughout the draft, and when the last pick 
rolled around, there was Finn. 
</P>
<P>
	Finn is fourth on Penn's career list with 2,277 yards rushing,  
and fifth with 180 points scored. He's also been used as a 
third-down receiver, and at 255 pounds, the Bears think he'll be a 
good blocker. 
</P>
<P>
	And then there are those ``intangibles'' coaches love to talk  
about on draft day. He's an Ivy Leaguer -- just like new coach Dick 
Jauron, though Jauron is a Yalie. And, Hatley said, Finn went to 
Penn, alma mater of Bears' chairman emeritus Ed McCaskey. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was one of those things that all fell in place,'' Hatley  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
