<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ruiz, Sorgi Dominate Diving Finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Mark Ruiz, competing in his hometown, and  
Californian Erica Sorgi continued their superiority over the rest 
of the field in the final day of action at the U.S. Spring National 
Diving Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruiz, 20, won his third and fourth national titles of the week,  
claiming individual honors in the men's platform 10-meter finals 
and combining with Justin Dumais to win the men's synchronized 
platform title. 
</P>
<P>
	Sorgi, 16, of Mission Viejo, won her second individual title in  
as many days, following up her triumph in the 3M with a first-place 
finish in the platform event. 
</P>
<P>
	Ruiz earned his win with a final score of 642.51, nearly 30  
points better than that of Troy Dumais. 
</P>
<P>
	In Saturday's 3-meter finals, Troy Dumais also finished second,  
but the circumstances were much different. He led Ruiz heading into 
the final round of dives before a late surge and faulty final dive 
cost him the championship. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no such drama in the platform event. Ruiz's victory  
was never in doubt, as the partisan crowd cheered his every dive. 
</P>
<P>
	With individual victories in the 1-meter, 3-meter, and platform  
events, Ruiz becomes the first diver to achieve that feat since 
Greg Louganis did it in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	The hat trick was even sweeter because it came in front of  
friends and family at an event only a few miles from his home. 
</P>
<P>
	``Doing it at home is the best part of it. I kept thinking,  
'What would it be like to win three in a row?' Even before the meet 
started, I thought about it,'' Ruiz said. ``It's a marathon though, 
really an exhausting week. I dove in every event and reached all of 
the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really couldn't have done it without the fans. I wanted to  
do it for them, and it is thanks to them that it happened. I'm just 
happy that they came out to support me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to his second-place finish, Troy Dumais will join Ruiz at  
the Pan American and World University Games. Mike Collier and 
Justin Dumais -- Troy's brother -- finished third and fourth, 
respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Justin Dumais and Ruiz ran away with the synchronized platform  
event, making the national team, along with second-place finishers 
Josh Edelman and Adam Hazes. 
</P>
<P>
	Sorgi won the platform event relatively easily. Her score of  
478.92 was over 24 points better than Kathy Pesek. 
</P>
<P>
	Both qualified for the Pan American and World University Games.  
</P>
<P>
	Sorgi has now won five national titles, but her sweep of the  
3-meter and platform events is the first time she's ever won both 
in the same competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely a step in the right direction for me,'' Sorgi  
said. ``This platform win is satisfying because it's only the 
second time I've competed in it at Nationals. It's about a year 
before the Olympics, so I'm definitely improving. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've still got a way to go, but I'm really happy.''  
</P>
<P>
	In the women's synchronized platform finals, Kristen Link and  
Lindsay Long defeated Laura Wilkinson and Patty Armstrong. But both 
pair made the national team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
