<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Africans Sweep the London Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Africans swept the London Marathon today, with  
Joyce Chepchumba of Kenya setting a world record. 
</P>
<P>
	Sort of.  
</P>
<P>
	While Abdelkader El Mouaziz became the first Morrocan to win the  
race, finishing in 2 hours, 7 minutes, 57 seconds, Chepchumba 
captured the women's division for the second time. 
</P>
<P>
	She was timed in 2 hours, 23 minutes, 22 seconds and earned  
$230,000, which included bonus money for a world mark recognized by 
the organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	Her time actually was the 12th fastest by a woman and later in  
the day became the 13th after Tegla Loroupe of Kenya ran 2:22.49 in 
Rotterdam, Netherlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Chepchumba's time also was more than 2:30 slower that Loroupe's  
official world record of 2:20.47 set at Rotterdam last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But the leading marks all were set in mixed races, where the  
women have the advantage of running alongside the faster men. 
</P>
<P>
	The women in the London Marathon start a half hour early so they  
won't be affected by the men's race. Organizers offered a bonus of 
$125,000 for anyone beating Lidia Simon's mark of 2:23.24, which 
was set by the Romanian in a women's-only race at Osaka, Japan, in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	Chepchumba also collected $55,000 for winning the race, $25,000  
more for a course record and a $25,000 time bonus for finishing 
inside 2:24.00. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I'll buy a new dress,'' Chepchumba said after learning  
of her $230,000 payday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 28-year-old Kenyan mother, who is a close friend of  
Loroupe's, said she believed she deserved the bonuses. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the men run with the women you get a better time,'' she  
said. ``But I think it's better for the women to run on their 
own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manuela Machado, a Portuguese world champion marathon runner who  
placed third behind Chepchumba and Adriana Fernandez of Mexico, 
agreed the Loroupe's performance in Rotterdam last year was not as 
good. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that Joyce's time is more special,'' she said.  
``When Tegla ran in Rotterdam she had two pacemakers. I value 
Joyce's time better than Tegla's.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez placed second in 2:24.06 and Machado was third in  
2:25.09 but neither could stay with Chepchumba. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kenyan hit the front three miles from home to maintain her  
remarkable record in the race. Her finishing positions in the four 
London Marathons are second in 1996, first in '97, third last year 
and now a winner again. 
</P>
<P>
	El Mouaziz, who led last year's race until fading to second,  
stayed close to the leaders of the strong field before breaking 
away with nine miles to go. 
</P>
<P>
	The Moroccan was never threatened and missed the course record  
by a second. Two-time champion Antonio Pinto of Portugal was 
second, 1:03 behind, and defending champ Abel Anton of Spain third 
in 2:09.41. 
</P>
<P>
	World record-holder Ronaldo Da Costs of Brazil was 17th, more  
than eight minutes slower than his mark of 2:06.05 set in Berlin 
last year. Olympic champion Josia Thugwane, who was among the 
leaders for half the race, dropped out at 22 miles when he 
developed a cough. 
</P>
<P>
	El Mouaziz, who slowed to wave several times to the crowd in the  
final 200 yards, didn't realize he was so close to the course 
record, which would have earned him an extra $25,000 to go with his 
$55,000 for finishing first. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was sharing my victory with the people and I did not watch  
the time,'' he said. ``I was so happy. That's why I lost the time 
and the big money.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
