<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 07:55:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Africans Sweep the London Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Africans swept the London Marathon on Sunday, with  
Abdelkader El Mouaziz becoming the first Morrocan to win the race 
and Joyce Chepchumba of Kenya capturing the women's division for 
the second time. 
</P>
<P>
	Chepchumba was timed in 2 hours, 23 minutes, 22 seconds and  
earned a $125,000 bonus for a world mark recognized by the 
organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	El Mouaziz, who led last year's race until he faded and finished  
second, broke away with nine miles to go and was timed in 2 hours, 
7 minutes, 57 seconds, missing the course record by a second. 
</P>
<P>
	Two-time champion Antonio Pinto was second, 1:03 behind, and  
defending champ Abdel Anton of Spain was third in 2:09.41. World 
record-holder Ronaldo Da Costs of Brazil was 17th, more than eight 
minutes slower than his mark of 2:06.05 set in Berlin last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Chepcumba shaved two seconds off the time owned by Lidia Simon  
and set in Osaka, Japan, in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Although there are 11 faster times among women, organizers of  
the London Marathon recognize it as the world's best because it was 
set in a women-only race. The other times were set in races that 
had a men's event as well and would have influenced the times. 
</P>
<P>
	Adriana Fernandez of Mexico placed second in 2:24.06 and world  
champion Manuela Machado of Portugal was third in 2:25.09. 
</P>
<P>
	Tegla Loroupe of Kenya, the woman who holds the world mark  
recognized by the International Amateur Athletic Federation, was 
running in Rotterdam and won in 2:22.49, the year's fastest time. 
She set the world mark 2:20.47 in Rotterdam last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
