seems unlikely, given that Milosevic's rejection of an 
international force doomed the Kosovo peace talks in the first 
place. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO officials are studying a land corridor for humanitarian  
relief, but that step is unlikely, Bacon said last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon emphasized the complications NATO would face in attempting  
a land invasion: mountainous terrain limits attack routes from 
Macedonia and Albania; few navigable roads; and Serb artillery and 
mined bridges. 
</P>
<P>
	Attacking from the north, through Hungary, would mean fighting  
the Serbs all the way to Kosovo in southern Serbia, Bacon said, 
suggesting that was an unlikely option. 
</P>
<P>
	Even getting troops to the area would be hard, Bacon said, given  
the lack of major ports and airfields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
