<HEADLINE> Egyptian Subway Opens Under Nile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Egypt's President Hosni Mubarak inaugurated  
a new stage of Cairo's subway Sunday that will take trains under 
the Nile, Egyptian radio reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Mubarak pushed the button to start the first train along a  
three-mile track from downtown Cairo through a 633-yard tunnel 
under the river to the city's university in the western suburb of 
Giza, the radio said. 
</P>
<P>
	The line is to be extended by next year to a spot near the  
pyramids and will eventually be about 12 miles long, the 
government-run newspaper Al-Ahram reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The $7 billion subway project has two lines now operating. Its  
trains carry about 1.7 million passengers a day. 
</P>
<P>
	The subway is the only one in the Middle East and Africa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
