<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A man trying to steal a car with California  
license plates was shot by a federal highway patrolman, Mexico City 
police reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Manuel Dominguez Montalvo approached the car in Mexico City with  
a gun on Saturday in an attempt to steal it, according to a police 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	But the driver, highway patrolman Ivan Daniel Jimenez Macglufde,  
pulled out his gun and the two exchanged shots. Both were seriously 
wounded and being treated at local hospitals on Sunday, the 
statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- Zapatista rebels are  
calling for a meeting of supporters from throughout Mexico to 
discuss the results of a nationwide referendum. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement issued late Saturday night, the Zapatista  
National Liberation Army said the meeting would be held May 7-10 in 
La Realidad, a remote village in southern Mexico that serves as the 
Zapatistas' unofficial capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebel leader Subcomandante Marcos said the gathering would  
discuss the results of a Zapatista referendum held across Mexico on 
March 21. 
</P>
<P>
	The Zapatistas claim that 95 percent of the 2.5 million people  
who participated expressed support for their position on Indian 
rights, though the wording of the referendum made ``no'' votes 
unlikely. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebels are trying to build support for their version of a  
plan for greater Indian rights. The government claims it has 
reached an agreement with the rebels, but has worded its version in 
a way that gives somewhat less autonomy to Indian communities than 
does the Zapatista version. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Rio de Janeiro's beaches were  
deserted Sunday while workers repaired a sewage pipeline that pumps 
waste out to sea. 
</P>
<P>
	Tons of raw sewage was being diverted to runoff pipes near  
normally busy beaches, making the water a health hazard. Work on 
the pipeline is expected to continue until next weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	City council officials on Sunday handed out leaflets in  
Portugese and English to residents and tourists to alert them to 
the danger. 
</P>
<P>
	``In five or six days the work will have finished and we will be  
able to open up the beaches for everyone,'' Andre Correa, Rio's 
Environmental Secretary, said in a televised interview. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- Colombian President  
Andres Pastrana met with Cuba's Fidel Castro on Sunday and 
discussed his demand that leftist guerrillas release 32 hostages 
seized in an April 12 plane hijacking. 
</P>
<P>
	Pastrana said he had ``shared information'' about the hijacking  
and other matters with Castro, but that there was no talk of Castro 
mediating an end to the standoff. 
</P>
<P>
	The two spoke following a weekend summit of the Association of  
Caribbean States in Santo Domingo. 
</P>
<P>
	Pastrana has been trying to win Castro's help in negotiating  
with the communist rebels. He asked Castro to mediate talks during 
a visit to Havana in January, but Castro has been noncommittal. 
Cuba's communist government actively supported Marxist-inspired 
rebel movements throughout Latin America in the 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	Pastrana, who said Friday that he won't negotiate the release of  
those it says were seized by the National Liberation Army, 
expressed frustration that the kidnappers had not issued demands. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they don't want to talk, if they don't want to negotiate,  
that's where the problem is,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia's government has accused the guerrillas of hijacking  
the Avianca flight and hauling its passengers and crew deep into 
rebel-held territory. The captors have released nine passengers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
