<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 10:49:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Exercise Machines May Lie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Do exercise machines lie?  
</P>
<P>
	The machines give you readouts of how many calories you burned,  
but experts say the readouts sometimes shade the truth. The 
machines can't account for factors ranging from the skill of the 
exerciser to the quality of the equipment's maintenance. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no way these things can be 100 percent accurate,''  
said Mike May, a spokesman for the Sporting Goods Manufacturers 
Association, a trade group. ``In some cases, it's an 
understatement; in others, it's an overstatement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The machines can get close, however, and this should be enough  
to get the workout job done, the experts said. 
</P>
<P>
	The machines base their calculations on standard formulas that  
predict how many calories a person should burn doing the exercise, 
said Richard Cotton, chief exercise physiologist for the American 
Council on Exercise, a fitness professionals' group based in San 
Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	The formulas ``are average for the whole population,'' Cotton  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The trouble is that people can differ from the average. One  
variable is the efficiency of the exerciser's body in doing the 
workout. On a treadmill, for instance, some people lumber along 
while others are so graceful they seem to float. 
</P>
<P>
	The floaters are more efficient and therefore use less energy at  
the same speed or intensity. Similarly, a novice, who would move 
less efficiently, also would burn more calories. 
</P>
<P>
	An exercise that keeps more body parts moving, such as running,  
would have more room for variation than would an exercise that 
allows less motion, such as biking, said Harv Ebel, a project 
leader at Consumer Reports magazine. As a result, a treadmill 
workout could allow more variation than a ride on a stationary 
bike. 
</P>
<P>
	To make a reading better fit an individual exerciser, a  
higher-end machine lets the user key in important personal data 
such as weight. ``If (the machine) never asks you to punch in your 
body weight, it is impossible for that machine to be accurate,'' 
Ebel said. 
</P>
<P>
	The more weight that has to be lifted during the exercise, the  
more calories are burned. As a result, weight is a bigger variable 
for a walker or runner than it is for a biker, whose lower body is 
supported by the seat. 
</P>
<P>
	ICON Health and Fitness of Logan, Utah, a leading treadmill  
manufacturer, gears the caloric expenditure of its lower-end 
machines for a person in the 150-185-pound range, spokeswoman Renee 
Awana said. An individual who wants a more accurate reading would 
have to do some math, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The user can divide his or her weight by 185, take that number  
and multiply it by the number of calories displayed,'' Awana said. 
For example, if you weigh 235 pounds, you would divide 235 by 185, 
getting 1.27, and multiply this by the readout of the calories 
burned. If the treadmill says you burned 100 calories, the more 
accurate total would be 127 calories, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher-end machines need only to be given the weight, and they  
do the math, Awana said. 
</P>
<P>
	But even equipment that does the math tends to have problems in  
keeping the numbers straight, Ebel said. In one test on various 
brands, the machines indicated the runner was going a bit faster 
than Consumer Reports lab tests found the belt actually was moving, 
he said. This would give an exerciser a somewhat overblown sense of 
accomplishment, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Intuitively, it would make sense,'' Ebel said. ``If they said  
it was a bit higher than it is, it makes you feel good about using 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And maintenance slippage can allow such things as belt slippage,  
which can throw the readings off, Cotton said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, if a person uses the same equipment all the time, the  
lack of a perfect calorie count may not matter, Cotton said. The 
machines tend to be consistent in their errors, so any improvement 
in exercise will show up as a better reading on the machine, even 
if it's not quite the right reading, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
