<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Stagger Toward NBA Playoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- More than ever, Shaquille O'Neal looked  
like one man against the world. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Los Angeles Lakers' 109-93 loss to the Utah Jazz on  
Saturday night, O'Neal was brilliant. He had 29 points, 14 rebounds 
and five blocks, humiliating every one of the four defenders the 
Jazz put on him. 
</P>
<P>
	Utah's only remedy was to double- and sometimes triple-team him.  
When the Jazz collapsed on him, O'Neal usually found the open man -- 
and then tried to rebound his teammates' missed shots. And there 
were plenty of those. 
</P>
<P>
	His frustration on the court was obvious. Afterward, he slumped  
at his locker, his loud Hawaiian-print shirt the only animated 
thing about him. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is gut-check time for this team,'' O'Neal said. ``I thought  
we played hard. I'm really proud of my guys today. ... They showed 
a lot of effort and a lot of heart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With consecutive losses to Seattle, Portland and Utah in the  
last six days, the Lakers appear in disarray with just nine games 
left before the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The three defeats all came against playoff contenders, and the  
Lakers must play three games in three nights starting Monday at 
home against Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
	``With all that controversy going on down there, it's got to be  
tough to play,'' Utah's Bryon Russell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Lakers remain convinced they can turn their season  
around. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our last couple of practices have been pretty good,'' said  
Kobe Bryant, who was 6-of-16 from the field and made four 
turnovers. ``Everybody's working hard, everybody's paying 
attention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not going to turn around overnight,'' coach Kurt Rambis  
said. ``As a whole, we're showing progress. We're working on 
everything, and we're going to get better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers set a new course on Thursday when they declared their  
midseason experiment a failure and waived seven-time rebounding 
champion Dennis Rodman. But on Saturday it was clear why they 
rolled the dice on the Tattooed One in the first place. 
</P>
<P>
	Karl Malone had his way with J.R. Reid, Robert Horry and Travis  
Knight, scoring 27 points and going to the line 14 times. Los 
Angeles needs the defense and rebounding at power forward that 
Rodman was supposed to provide, but never did. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have an opinion,'' O'Neal said of Rodman's departure.  
He also declined to speak on the subject Friday, a day after Rodman 
was waived. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's behind us,'' Derek Fisher said. ``All we were focusing  
on was today's basketball game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers got Glen Rice and Knight back in the lineup Saturday,  
but neither contributed much. Knight was scoreless in 17 minutes, 
though he played better defense than Reid, who scored one point in 
27 minutes of his first Lakers' start. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice, who missed two games with tonsillitis, still isn't in the  
flow. He was 4-of-10 and disappeared in the third quarter, when the 
Jazz pulled away. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the schedule is not easy. The Lakers play Portland  
three times and travel to Houston and San Antonio. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers are practically locked into fourth or fifth place in  
the Western Conference. That probably means a first-round matchup 
with the Rockets, with the winner facing the Jazz or the Trail 
Blazers in the conference semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm always keeping my spirits up, no matter what happens,''  
O'Neal said. ``Good times are ahead, hopefully. I always keep my 
spirit up. Nothing can break it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
