<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Hear Disabled Care Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MORROW, Ga. (AP) -- Three years ago, Elaine Wilson sat in a state  
mental hospital wearing little more than a sheet, her eyes glazed 
and tongue lolling from medication. 
</P>
<P>
	``I barely remember that much. In the hospital, I felt like I  
was in a box that I would never get out of,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Ms. Wilson lives in a personal care home, where she cooks  
her own meals. She is learning math at a community-based day 
program that teaches life skills. 
</P>
<P>
	The 47-year-old, who has a personality disorder and suffered  
brain damage during a bout with meningitis, credits her turnaround 
to her new surroundings. 
</P>
<P>
	She is one of two plaintiffs in a Supreme Court case that could  
decide whether the Americans with Disabilities Act should force 
states to place mentally disabled patients into community settings, 
not hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	L.C. vs. Olmstead, which Ms. Wilson joined in 1996, will be  
argued Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The state's handling of Ms. Wilson's care, while not malicious,  
``was a pretty studied lack of effort that in our view was 
definitely inexcusable,'' said Sue Jamieson of Atlanta Legal Aid, 
who filed the suit for Lois Curtis and then added Ms. Wilson. 
``These two women were just stuck in a place where they didn't 
belong for as long as three years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jamieson filed the suit in May 1995 against Tommy Olmstead, the  
Commissioner of the Georgia Department of Human Resources, which 
runs the state mental hospital system. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though doctors said Ms. Curtis, who is schizophrenic and  
mentally retarded, was a candidate for community-based care, the 
state would release her only to her mother, who was unequipped to 
care for her. That prolonged her hospital stay, although she is now 
in a personal care home. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Wilson had a similar recommendation from her doctors but was  
hospitalized for three years. 
</P>
<P>
	She gained her release only after the suit was upheld in both  
federal district and appeals courts. Georgia is asking the Supreme 
Court to overturn the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruling, 
which required the state to provide community-based care for Ms. 
Wilson and Ms. Curtis. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit argues that by refusing to place the two women in  
community care, the state violated the disabilities act, which 
requires programs to place the disabled in the ``most integrated 
setting possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state counters that the services weren't provided to Ms.  
Curtis and Ms. Wilson because no space was available in existing 
programs and creating new ones would be too expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	The state mental health budget is $696.8 million, a figure that  
would dramatically increase if a massive switch to community 
services is mandated. 
</P>
<P>
	``The state cannot comply with its duty to provide adequate  
facility (institution) programs if it moves any more of its 
facility funds to community programs,'' Assistant Georgia Attorney 
General Patricia Downing argued in her brief. 
</P>
<P>
	She also said such a far-reaching decision would be a violation  
of states' rights. Twenty-two states initially endorsed Georgia's 
position and another four joined later, but 19 of the 26 have since 
pulled out. 
</P>
<P>
	Many mental-health advocates say the states want to keep  
hospitals running at capacity to save themselves the political 
headaches that come with cutting state jobs and facing angry 
health-care worker unions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very clear this ruling could mean a lot of jobs are  
downsized, and people are fighting it,'' said Ira Burnim, legal 
director for the Washington-based Bazelon Center for Mental Health 
Law. 
</P>
<P>
	But other advocates say changing too fast can create problems at  
both the state and private level. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people could end up at programs that are not equipped to  
handle their expensive medical and psychological needs,'' said 
Tamie Hopp, executive director of Voice of the Retarded, which 
endorses the 11th Circuit ruling but wants hospitals to be kept 
open. ``When you start shutting down hospitals, people are without 
that choice as well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Wilson doesn't care what the Supreme Court rules, as long as  
she never has to go back to the Georgia Regional Hospital at 
Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``All you did there was eat, get a shower or maybe smoke a  
cigarette,'' she said. ``No privacy neither. I feel like a real 
person again, and no one is going to take that away from me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
