<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Antigua Replaces Bank Overseers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) -- Antigua has replaced the overseers of  
its offshore banks, acting after the United States charged it was 
undermining money-laundering efforts and urged U.S. banks to 
closely scrutinize transactions from the Caribbean island. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister John St. Luce told reporters the former British  
colony also shortly will amend money-laundering legislation ``to 
make Antigua one of the safest and most desirable locations for 
international banking in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference Friday, St. Luce insisted that the  
government is ``very keen to continue our efforts with the 
international community to block every loophole for financial 
crime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said none of the new overseers are tied to offshore banks -- a  
reference to the U.S. complaint that four of six of the previous 
board members represented the institutions they were supposed to 
regulate. 
</P>
<P>
	The new board includes former banker and current Health Minister  
Bernard Percival, as chairman, prominent businessman and former 
banker Jose Benjamin, Deputy Financial Secretary Eustace Peters, 
former Police Commissioner Edric Potter, Antigua's ambassador to 
the United States, Lionel Hurst, and Minister of State Assot 
Michael as deputy chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 7, the U.S. Treasury Department urged U.S. banks and  
savings institutions to more closely scrutinize all financial 
transactions in and out of Antigua and Barbuda, saying recent 
government actions there ``will undermine U.S. efforts to crack 
down on international money laundering.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was only the second time in three years that the department  
has targeted a specific country in an advisory. The first, in March 
1996, was aimed at the Seychelles. 
</P>
<P>
	Antigua and Barbuda, population 64,000, has 50 banks primarily  
serving offshore clients. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. treasury said the government had significantly weakened  
its anti-money laundering law in November, by strengthening bank 
secrecy rules and inhibiting investigations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
