<DOCNO> APW19990418.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 23:23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Chepchumba Sets World Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Hear about the world marathon record that wasn't?  
</P>
<P>
	Kenyan friends Joyce Chepchumba and Tegla Loroupe won the London  
and Rotterdam Marathons on the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	World record holder Loroupe cruised to a faster time than her  
countrywoman, yet Chepchumba collected $230,000 in prizes and 
bonuses for setting a world mark over the same distance of 26 
miles, 385 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Puzzled?  
</P>
<P>
	Let the organizers of the London Marathon explain.  
</P>
<P>
	Chepchumba's time of 2 hours, 23 minutes, 22 seconds actually  
was only the 12th fastest by a woman, and later in the day became 
the 13th after Loroupe ran 2:22.49 in Rotterdam. It also was more 
than 2 1/2 minutes slower than Loroupe's official world record of 
2:20.47 set at Rotterdam last year. 
</P>
<P>
	But the leading marks all were set in mixed races, where the  
women have the advantage of running alongside the faster men. 
</P>
<P>
	The women in the London Marathon start a half hour early so they  
won't be affected by the men's race, which was won by Morocco's 
Abdelkader El Mouaziz. Organizers offered a bonus of $125,000 for 
anyone beating Lidia Simon's mark of 2:23.24, which was set by the 
Romanian in a women's-only race at Osaka, Japan, in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Chepchumba also collected $55,000 for winning Sunday's race,  
$25,000 more for a course record and a $25,000 time bonus for 
finishing inside 2:24.00. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I'll buy a new dress,'' Chepchumba said after learning  
of her $230,000 payday. 
</P>
<P>
	But she was adamant that her performance was better than the  
official world record Loroupe set last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the men run with the women, you get a better time,'' she  
said. ``But I think it's better for the women to run on their 
own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manuela Machado, a Portuguese world champion marathon runner who  
placed third behind Chepchumba and Adriana Fernandez of Mexico, 
agreed the Loroupe's performance in Rotterdam last year was not as 
good. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that Joyce's time is more special,'' she said.  
``When Tegla ran in Rotterdam, she had two pacemakers. I value 
Joyce's time better than Tegla's.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez placed second in 2:24.06 and Machado was third in  
2:25.09. 
</P>
<P>
	El Mouaziz scored a runaway victory in the men's race and would  
have set a course record if he hadn't slowed to wave to the fans in 
the final 200 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	He clocked 2:07.57 to leave behind the strongest ever field in  
the 19th London Marathon. Two-time titlist Antonio Pinto finished 
second, 1:03 behind, and defending champ Abel Anton of Spain was 
third in 2:09.41. 
</P>
<P>
	World record-holder Ronaldo Da Costa of Brazil was 17th, more  
than eight minutes slower than his mark of 2:06.05 set in Berlin 
last year. Olympic champion Josia Thugwane, who was among the 
leaders for half the race, dropped out at 22 miles when he 
developed a cough. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990418.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 23:23:58 </DATE_TIME>
