<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Federal Bank To Appeal Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- California Federal Bank will appeal a $23.3  
million award to the savings and loan, calling the judgment 
``flawed.'' The bank originally had sought more than $1.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``The $23.3 million award falls far short of CalFed's actual  
damages,'' spokesman Walter G. Montgomery said Sunday in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Robert H. Hodges Jr. of the U.S. Court of Federal Claims  
on Friday found the government breached its contract with CalFed. 
</P>
<P>
	The case stems from a 1996 Supreme Court decision that said the  
government broke its contract with thrift institutions when it 
changed the rules on how they must count their assets as part of an 
S&AMP;L bailout in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	CalFed said last week's decision is ``flawed'' and agrees  
``neither with applicable law nor with the extensive evidence and 
testimony presented at trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	San Francisco-based Golden State Bancorp is the publicly traded  
parent company of CalFed. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990418.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 10:32:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Helps Resolve Phone, TV Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- It's tempting to sum up Susan Ness as the June  
Cleaver type. But behind her nurturing way is an agile power broker 
whose political and business savvy makes her good at settling 
disputes involving the nation's television and telephone systems. 
</P>
<P>
	In her five years as a member of the Federal Communications  
Commission, Ness has emerged as a crucial bridge between the 
agency's liberal and conservative factions, and an effective 
dealmaker at an agency that oversees roughly one-seventh of the 
nation's economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``She doesn't come across as an aggressive person, but she knows  
what she wants and goes after it,'' said a friend, Supreme Court 
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg. ``You talk to Susan and you sense that 
you are getting an honest count.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Ginsburg was picked by President Carter to serve on the  
federal court here, it was Ness who had the savvy to take her to a 
centrist Republican whose support helped overcome what Ginsburg 
herself called her ``flaming feminist'' image among some 
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Ness' friendship with first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton -- they  
met at a Renaissance weekend in 1983 -- paved the way for her 
nomination to the FCC. 
</P>
<P>
	The most senior of the agency's five commissioners, Ness is  
there at a time when the FCC is treading difficult political and 
policymaking waters. Key Republican lawmakers are upset over the 
agency's implementation of a 1996 law deregulating the 
telecommunications industries. They want to strip away some of its 
power, particularly over mergers. 
</P>
<P>
	Keeping pace with rapidly changing technology and with companies  
that don't fit neatly into one framework is another challenge: Is 
AT&AMP;T a telephone company, a cable television service, an Internet 
provider or all three? The agency also is overseeing broadcasters' 
move into digital, an issue Ness will speak about as the industry 
gathers for its annual meeting in Las Vegas this week. 
</P>
<P>
	``She knows a lot about this profession, but she doesn't wear it  
on her sleeve. She's just very solid,'' said another friend, Ann 
Lewis, counselor to President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Ness takes as much pride in being a mother as a senior  
government official. Son, David, 10, is a computer whiz who freely 
offers technical advice. Elisabeth, 14, sings, dances and acts in 
school plays. Ness always carries in her leather calendar a note 
Elisabeth, then 9, wrote on the day of her mother's Senate 
confirmation hearing. ``Good Luck. You needn't be nervous. You are 
my Mom and shall always be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some telecommunications lobbyists call Ness the FCC's in-house  
Mom, too. But Ness, unassuming and unfailingly polite, uses those 
traits to her advantage, drawing people to her for advice, to build 
consensus or to break through impasses. 
</P>
<P>
	When broadcasters, TV set makers, computer and cable TV guys  
were at loggerheads over digital TV technical standards several 
years ago and refused to deal with then-FCC chairman Reed Hundt, 
they sought out Ness. She quietly took control, steering and 
pushing them to reach agreement, giving deadlines, building public 
support. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question that she was the linchpin,'' recalls Peter  
Fannon, now an executive with Panasonic. The agreement is now a 
blueprint for building new digital TV sets, just now cropping up in 
stores. 
</P>
<P>
	When Hundt wanted to bail out overeager, but underfunded bidders  
for mobile phone licenses, Ness forged a compromise giving the 
companies some relief but requiring them to still come up with 
money. She also brokered a compromise that gave schools cheap 
hookups to the Internet and was a prominent figure in negotiations 
-- ultimately clinched by the White House -- that led to broadcasters 
having to air three hours of educational children's' programs a 
week. Both were key White House issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, despite her connection to Mrs. Clinton, the White House  
passed her over for chairman in 1996. Ness didn't have a champion 
in Clinton's inner circle and various industry groups preferred 
others, say those involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Ness' term expires June 30 and it's unclear whether Clinton  
will reappoint her. Senate Commerce Committee John McCain, R-Ariz., 
must clear any nomination and McCain generally believes 
commissioners should serve only one term. Ness could continue to 
serve for at least another year without being reappointed. Were she 
to leave and a successor not immediately take her place, the FCC 
could end up with paralyzing 2-2 deadlocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Ness won't discuss her prospects. ``All I will tell you is that  
I love what I do,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer with an MBA from Wharton, Ness has more business  
experience than any member now on the FCC. For years she was a 
banker lending money to TV, radio, cable and telephone companies. A 
self-described pragmatic policy-maker who shuns the term 
``regulator,'' she asks: ``You can have all kinds of requirements 
but who is going to pay for them? Consumers?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer advocate Gene Kimmelman gives Ness high marks for  
protecting telephone consumers, but complains she didn't do enough 
to protect TV watchers from rising cable rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Some broadcasters, telephone executives and lawmakers, on the  
other hand, think she's too regulatory. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't always agree,'' said Jeffrey Smulyan, chairman of  
Emmis Communications Corp., a large broadcasting company. ``But I 
never doubted that she has great concern of the impact that we have 
on people's lives.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990418.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 15:38:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Confusion in NATO Account of Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Confusion over a deadly attack on a  
Kosovo refugee convoy deepened Sunday after NATO said a tape of a 
pilot it presented after the attack may not be the pilot who 
attacked the convoy. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington has said the pilot on the tape described a strike  
against military targets -- without hitting civilians. However, NATO 
Brig. Gen. Giuseppe Marani said the pilot may indeed have struck 
civilians, adding that NATO is awaiting the results of an inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Marani said he produced the tape as ``an example'' of how a  
pilot reacts during a ground attack over Kosovo and because ``that 
tape was clear, was available.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Yugoslav authorities said NATO planes had killed  
more than 60 Kosovo Albanians in an attack on a refugee column. A 
road strewn with refugee bodies was shown on Serbian television and 
foreign journalists were escorted to the site to film the carnage. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO acknowledged Thursday that at least one of its planes had  
mistakenly hit at least one civilian vehicle with fatal results. 
</P>
<P>
	``NATO deeply regrets the loss of life from this tragic  
accident,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said Thursday at the 
alliance's daily media briefing. 
</P>
<P>
	After Shea's introductory comments, Marani played a tape of what  
he said ``may be this incident.'' The F-16 pilot, who was not 
identified, described an attack on a three-vehicle convoy he 
believed to be military vehicles involved in burning villages. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, NATO has faced mounting criticism of its refusal to  
explain discrepancies between the mistaken strike it acknowledged 
and remains seen by journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO acknowledged hitting just one civilian vehicle, possibly a  
tractor on a road north of the Kosovo town Djakovica. The Serbs 
showed several vehicles hit on a road south of the town. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, Navy Capt. Steve Pietropaoli said Saturday that  
the pilot heard on the tape ``is not thought to be responsible in 
any way for anything other than the attack that he described on a 
military vehicle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Pietropaoli said he did not mean there was not an  
accidental attack on civilians in the area. ``It appears to be that 
that may be the case,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO's military command is refusing to offer any further details  
of the refugee attack pending results of an investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
