<HEADLINE> Boston Home for Patriots Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino says he's willing to  
back a stadium for the New England Patriots in Boston if the team's 
deal in Connecticut falls through. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Menino said there was no site in the city that was  
suitable for a Patriots stadium. But after a group of civic leaders 
went public Friday with a last-minute campaign to block the 
Patriots' move to Hartford, Conn., Menino said the stadium could be 
located on an old incinerator site south of downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not a new man,'' Menino told The Boston Globe. ``I'm an  
individual who doesn't close his mind to opportunities. If I have 
an opportunity to listen and to be convinced, I'm there to listen 
and be convinced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The civic leaders opposing the move to Hartford have the support  
of the NFL, which prefers that the team remain in the Boston area, 
the sixth largest television market in the country, rather than 
relocate to Hartford, where smaller audiences would mean less TV 
revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL recently approved new financing that could help defray  
the costs of constructing a new stadium for Kraft and other 
big-city team owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Even House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, who did not approve a  
deal last year to put the Patriots in a new stadium in Foxboro, was 
receptive to league officials when they paid him a visit Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it is far from certain that the Hartford deal will  
collapse and give Massachusetts another shot at retaining its 
football franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	After new stadium plans for South Boston and Foxboro were  
rejected, Kraft struck a $374 million accord with Gov. John Rowland 
of Connecticut that is considered the most lucrative deal ever for 
an NFL owner. 
</P>
<P>
	But the agreement has been plagued by ongoing problems with the  
Hartford site and questions about whether the stadium would be 
completed by 2002, when Kraft wants it to be ready. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of their preliminary agreement, Kraft can decide to  
abandon the Connecticut proposal by the end of April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
