<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holmgren Conservative in NFL Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) -- In his first NFL draft as general manager  
and coach of the Seattle Seahawks, Mike Holmgren didn't do anything 
drastic, as New Orleans' Mike Ditka did by trading eight draft 
picks for Ricky Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	But he seems to have had a solid draft. And he emulated the man  
he first worked for, Bill Walsh, with minor deals that netted him 
the players he wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Saturday's selection of defensive end Lamar King of  
Saginaw Valley State (Mich.) in the first round and Washington 
quarterback Brock Huard and Auburn wide receiver Karsten Bailey in 
the third, the Seahawks got two more defensive players, an 
offensive lineman and a specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	In the fourth round, they drafted defensive end Antonio Cochran  
of Georgia with the 115th selection. In the fifth round, they got 
6-foot-4, 333-pound tackle Floyd Wedderburn of Penn State and punt 
returner Charlie Rogers of Georgia Tech at No. 152. 
</P>
<P>
	Then in the sixth round, Holmgren packaged Seattle's two picks  
and traded them to Cleveland for the Browns' first pick in the 
round, to get Steve Johnson, a cornerback from Tennessee's national 
championship team. 
</P>
<P>
	Wedderburn was rated by some as one of the top offensive linemen  
available, but he dropped because of weight problems and knee 
injuries. Rogers is considered a handy utility man who can play 
wide receiver and running back as well as return kicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmgren's only regret: No tight end.  
</P>
<P>
	``I got the returner,'' Holmgren said. ``I got a little nervous  
because I had targeted two tight ends and I lost them both. 
</P>
<P>
	``My resident gurus were sitting there and I asked them if  
Johnson would be available when we drafted and they said, `Sure.' I 
said, `You told me that for those tight ends.' Then I said, `Let's 
trade the two picks up to Cleveland. I don't want to miss this 
guy.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Fritz Shurmur, Holmgren's defensive coordinator, was  
particularly happy with the addition of the 6-3, 273-pound Cochran 
to go along with Saturday's addition of King. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we talk about defensive linemen, we stay away from the  
undersized guys,'' Shurmur said. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmgren took the coaching job in Seattle -- signing an  
eight-year contract for $4 million a season -- so he could have the 
team's GM job, too. This weekend, he didn't have Packers GM Ron 
Wolf calling the shots over him. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmgren said he enjoyed his first draft as No. 1.  
</P>
<P>
	``I had a great time,'' he said. ``It was fun. The difference  
was as guys were coming off the board in years past, I didn't get 
so nervous. This year, I took it personally.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
