<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bob Beamon To Start Track Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) -- Bob Beamon, whose winning long jump at  
the 1968 Olympics stood as the world record for 23 years, was 
chosen to launch a track and field program at Florida Atlantic 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	Beamon, 52, was introduced Saturday as the school's director of  
development for track and field. The title is similar to one held 
at Florida Atlantic by Howard Schnellenberger, who is working to 
start a football program in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	FAU will field its first women's track team next spring, with  
the men's program to follow in 2001. The women's team is forming 
first to help comply with gender equity regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	``The addition of someone of Bob Beamon's stature shows how  
quickly Florida Atlantic's athletics program is maturing,'' said 
athletic director Tom Cargill, who brought Schnellenberger to 
direct football operations and recently hired former NBA player 
Sidney Green to coach men's basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	Beamon stunned the world with his leap of 29 feet, 2 1/2 inches to  
win the gold medal in Mexico City, shattering the previous mark by 
nearly two feet. The mark stood until Mike Powell jumped 29-4 1/2 at 
the 1991 World Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida Atlantic is Beamon's first Division I coaching position.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is just another challenge,'' he said. ``If my dreams can  
happen to me, your dreams can happen to you. Champions are not made 
on the track or field; champions are made by the things you 
accomplish and the way you use your abilities in everyday life 
situations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beamon previously worked with the Miami-Dade County Parks and  
Recreation Department and started several youth programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
