<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 15:32:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minnesota Hoops Squad Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHANHASSEN, Minn. (AP) -- Investigators looking into alleged  
academic fraud within the University of Minnesota men's basketball 
program were expected to meet Monday with the former director of 
the school's academic counseling unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Elayne Donahue last week released a long memo she wrote alleging  
the basketball program received preferential treatment from 
high-ranking university officials on academic issues under pressure 
from coach Clem Haskins. 
</P>
<P>
	Donahue said she went public with the information because she  
was concerned the investigators would overlook allegations not 
reported in the media, since they had not contacted her up to that 
point. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, the investigators, outside attorneys Donald Lewis  
and Michael Glazier, met for a fourth time with the woman whose 
allegations prompted the investigation, former office manager Jan 
Gangelhoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Jim Lord, who represents Gangelhoff and Donahue, said  
the investigators reviewed more of the estimated 400 pieces of 
course work Gangelhoff says she did for Gopher players, and for the 
first time discussed a $3,000 tutoring payment she says came from 
Haskins. 
</P>
<P>
	Gangelhoff has said academic counselor Alonzo Newby told her the  
money he handed her in June of 1998 came from Haskins and was 
payment for tutoring Antoine Broxsie during spring quarter that 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Haskins has denied paying Gangelhoff while Newby hasn't  
commented publicly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jan told investigators that after she was given the money she  
called Alonzo to tell him that she had received it,'' Lord said 
after the nearly five-hour session at his suburban office. ``Then, 
(Newby) told her that coach Haskins `was quite pained to have given 
up that much money.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Lord said much of the course work has yet to be reviewed, but no  
date had been set when Gangelhoff would be interviewed again. Lord 
also said it hadn't been decided when the investigators would meet 
with Jeanne Payer, Gangelhoff's sister, who has said Newby gave her 
the $3,000 to give to Gangelhoff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
