<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia Renews Offer for CNG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Columbia Energy Group renewed its effort  
today to buy Consolidated Natural Gas Co., despite a stock deal 
announced in February for Dominion Resources Inc. to acquire the 
Pittsburgh-based gas supplier. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy's $6.68 billion offer represents a 33.5 percent  
premium above CNG's closing share price and a 21 percent premium 
above Dominion Resources' offer. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hunter Applewhite, a spokesman for Dominion Resources, said  
the Richmond-based utility holding company already has a definitive 
merger agreement with CNG. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dominion Resources has the strength to offer the convergence  
of both electric and gas services to customers now and in the 
future,'' Applewhite said in a prepared statement. ``This makes our 
combination a superior one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Columbia Energy offer of $70 for each CNG share consists of  
$24.50 in Columbia Energy shares and $45.50 in cash. Columbia 
Energy would also assume $2 billion in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliver G. Richard III, chairman, president and chief executive  
officer of Columbia Energy, called his company's proposal ``a 
compelling combination for the shareholders and customers of both 
companies'' that would leave the combined business in a position 
``to prosper in the emerging deregulated energy industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe we are uniquely positioned to capture the full  
value of a combination with CNG and are hopeful that we will have 
the opportunity to explore such a merger more fully,'' Richard 
wrote in a letter to George A. Davidson Jr., chairman and CEO of 
CNG. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy had offered $66 to $70 a share for CNG two days  
before the deal with Dominion Resources was announced Feb. 22, 
according to Richard's letter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to believe a combination of our two companies  
would be an excellent financial and strategic fit,'' Richard wrote 
in seeking formal merger talks. ``... We have adequate sources of 
financing and therefore our proposal is not subject to any 
financing conditions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letter said the offer would be withdrawn May 3 if no  
favorable response is received. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Donovan, a spokesman for CNG, acknowledged the company had  
received the offer and said its board of directors ``will review it 
in due course.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CNG's deal with Dominion Resources was valued at $6.3 billion  
when it was announced, though is now worth about $5.5 billion. The 
merger would create a company serving nearly 4 million customers 
with $8.8 billion in annual revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	CNG shares closed Friday at $52.43 3/4 on the New York Stock  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Columbia Energy closed at $48.25 Friday, while shares  
of Dominion Resources closed at $38.06 1/4, both also on the NYSE. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy, based in Herndon in the northern Virginia  
suburbs of Washington, had 1998 revenues of nearly $6.6 billion. 
Its natural gas business includes exploration and production, 
transmission, storage and distribution, as well as propane sales 
and electric power generation. It serves customers in 34 states and 
the District of Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	CNG supplies natural gas to 1.9 million customers in Ohio,  
Pennsylvania, Virginia and West Virginia. It also owns 7,600 miles 
of gas pipelines in New York, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Virginia, West 
Virginia and Maryland. It had 1998 revenue of $2.76 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Dominion Resources, the parent company of electricity supplier  
Virginia Power, had $6 billion in revenues last year. It has 
operations in the United States, Canada, Great Britain, Argentina, 
Belize, Bolivia and Peru. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
