<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Littlebitlively Beats Real Quiet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas (AP) -- Littlebitlively held off a stretch  
run by 1998 Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner Real Quiet on 
Sunday and won the $250,000 Texas Mile for the second straight 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the eighth victory in 26 career starts for the horse  
trained by Bobby Barnett. 
</P>
<P>
	Real Quiet, trained by Bob Baffert and with Gary Stevens riding  
for the first time, caught Littlebitlively at the top of the 
stretch but couldn't put him away. Urged on by jockey Carlos 
Gonzalez, the winner surged back to beat Real Quiet, the 2-to-5 
favorite, by a neck. 
</P>
<P>
	``He just got outrun,'' Baffert said. ``A mile is just not his  
game. Longer races are his style and you can't change him. If Gary 
had rushed him he would have come up empty. It's just one of those 
deals. I was pleased with it. I would have liked to win but he got 
beat. If you get outrun, you get outrun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens said Real Quiet just got beat.  
</P>
<P>
	``Real Quiet got the lead at the turn so we have no excuses,''  
Stevens said. ``Littlebitlively is a tough little horse. We knew we 
would be in a battle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Littlebitlively, which paid $7.40 to win, loves the Lone Star  
Park track, Barnett said, and blinkers helped him concentrate. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's had some good works and (owner John Franks) and I decided  
it might be good for him if we put him in blinkers,'' Barnett said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez said Littlebitlively had plenty left at the end.  
</P>
<P>
	``I just kept trying to get him to relax,'' Gonzalez said. ``I  
think the blinkers really made the difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens was aboard Victory Gallop which beat Real Quiet by a  
nose at the Belmont Stakes last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens replaced Kent Desormeaux on last year's champion  
3-year-old. Stevens is the primary jockey for Baffert but was the 
rider on Silver Charm for many races last year. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the shortest race for Real Quiet who had never won a race  
at a distance of less than 1 1-16 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	Julie Krone, who retired after the day's racing, finished third  
on Allen's Oop. 
</P>
<P>
	``Littlebitlively showed a lot but we almost caught him and Real  
Quiet,'' Krone said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
