<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judy Collins Talks About Addiction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Judy Collins says just saying ``no'' is  
just not that easy. 
</P>
<P>
	The folk singer says the famous anti-drug campaign wrongly looks  
at drug and alcohol addiction as a character flaw. 
</P>
<P>
	``It assumes that those who are locked up because of it just  
didn't have the willpower to carry out their plan for the 
evening,'' Collins told The Tennessean in an interview published 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she knows from personal experience that addiction is  
not a choice and is often inherited. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, a former alcoholic who has abstained from liquor and  
drugs for 20 years, said she began drinking as a 15-year-old to 
mask the shame and pain that her own father's alcoholism caused 
her. 
</P>
<P>
	Her only son, Clark, a drug addict and an alcoholic, killed  
himself in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have an illness,'' she said of addicts. ``My desire is to  
talk about the public education about this disease and about how 
far short it falls.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990418.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 10:52:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Habit of Dirt-Eating Is Studied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- As a nurse, Rena Bronson knows eating dirt can  
cause anemia, constipation and serious liver and kidney damage. But 
that doesn't seem to matter when her body starts yearning for those 
crumbly white chunks of clay. 
</P>
<P>
	Her 10-year, $1.48-a-bag kaolin habit has left the 51-year-old  
woman lethargic, isolated and chronically constipated. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have much of a social life anymore,'' she said. ``It's  
more important I get home to get my fix.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dirt eating, or geophagy, goes back thousands of years. The  
ancient Greeks ate clay to fight a variety of ailments. About 2,000 
years later, the practice continues, especially among poor folks in 
rural middle Georgia -- where most of the world's kaolin comes from. 
</P>
<P>
	Women, pregnant women in particular, say the white clay settles  
their stomachs. Ms. Bronson says the taste is hard to describe. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you know how the ground smells when it's real dry and along  
comes a little sprinkle of rain -- that fresh smell? If you could 
taste a smell, that's how I would describe it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most people expect it to be gritty, but it's creamy smooth.  
</P>
<P>
	``Technically, I'd rather eat dirt than food,'' she said. ``If I  
could eat dirt for breakfast, dirt for lunch, dirt for dinner and a 
little iced tea I'd be fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is, no matter what name you call it -- dirt, clay, or  
chalk -- kaolin simply isn't supposed to be eaten. The fine white 
mineral is used in papermaking, paint products, ceramics, 
fiberglass and stomach-soothing medicines. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia produces about 8 million tons of kaolin a year -- or half  
the world's supply -- making it easy for Ms. Bronson and an untold 
number of others to find. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people just go out and dig in their yard. But I've seen  
it at convenience stores, stores in black neighborhoods, gas 
stations,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though it says right on the package that it's a novelty  
item `not for human consumption,' sometimes you'll find it with the 
vegetables at the grocery store.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sweet Auburn farmer's market in downtown Atlanta, for  
example, piles its Ziplock packages of white dirt in a basket next 
to the peanuts. 
</P>
<P>
	People who eat kaolin are not addicted and are not suffering  
from a psychiatric disorder, according to R. Kevin Grigsby, a 
social worker and professor of psychiatry and health behavior at 
the Medical College of Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he said, little is known about this particular form of pica  
-- the term used to describe the persistent eating of nonfood items. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are many types of pica -- eating burned matches, ice and,  
in this case, earth,'' said Grigsby, the primary author of a recent 
study on kaolin eating in central Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Grigsby said he and his colleagues discovered they were delving  
into uncharted territory with the study, featured in the February 
issue of the Southern Medical Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one has really studied kaolin-specific pica,'' he said.  
``What we discovered was people were very reluctant to talk about 
chalk eating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bronson was no exception.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's embarrassing for me. It's embarrassing for my family. But  
if it can help someone, I'm willing to put up with that 
embarrassment,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bronson, the oldest of 13 children, remembers seeing her  
mother eat kaolin while she was pregnant. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mama would give us 15 cents and say, `Go up to so-and-so's  
house and get me some chalk,'' she said. ``Naturally, as a child 
you're going to taste it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She made it through two pregnancies without giving white dirt a  
second thought. It wasn't until years later that she found herself 
pinching a piece here and there. Eventually, she started buying 
bags of her own. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of the sudden, I'd say within a year, it was like -- `I  
want that.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, she said she goes through about three bags a week.  
</P>
<P>
	Grigsby's study found that dirt eating was most common among  
black women in rural areas who were introduced to it by a relative. 
</P>
<P>
	The study stressed that physicians need to be made aware of the  
behavior and said additional research was needed to determine the 
scope of the problem and the extent of its health repercussions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't reached the point yet where I sit down and tell  
myself I am not going to do this anymore,'' Ms. Bronson said. 
``Once I do, then I feel reasonably sure I just won't do it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990418.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 13:33:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Says Milosevic Is 'Tyrant' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton branded Slobodan Milosevic a  
``belligerent tyrant'' and said Sunday the Yugoslav president could 
not be part of any democratic transition by his nation into a free 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing in a London newspaper, Clinton said NATO airstrikes that  
began March 24 will continue until Milosevic's Serb forces are too 
weak to fight in Kosovo or until he agrees to peace and autonomy 
for the Serbian province's ethnic Albanians. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our campaign will continue, shifting the balance of power  
against him until we succeed,'' Clinton said in an opinion piece in 
the Sunday Times. ``Ultimately, Mr. Milosevic must either cut his 
mounting losses or lose his ability to maintain his grip on 
Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also Sunday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said NATO  
airstrikes at oil refineries, ammunition depots and Serb military 
command and control centers are ``wearing down'' Milosevic's 
military and choking off vital supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the administration is acting to prevent ``outside  
powers'' from delivering oil to the Serb military through ports in 
Montenegro, a second Yugoslav republic. Albright did not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials also are giving an international war crimes  
tribunal evidence of suspected Serb atrocities. The information 
includes satellite photos of mass graves and reports of ethnic 
Albanian women being raped and civilians slaughtered. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright, blaming Milosevic, said on ABC's ``This Week'': ``It  
is harder and harder to imagine the U.S. could negotiate with 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Albright repeated the administration's position against  
using ground troops, members of Congress said that stand only helps 
Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``To rule out any option obviously has to be nothing but an  
encouragement to Mr. Milosevic to hunker down, and it's distressing 
that we continue to not acknowledge that fact,'' GOP Sen. John 
McCain of Arizona, a presidential hopeful, said on ABC. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., said lawmakers should ``push the  
president ... to muster up the courage'' to consider using ground 
troops to oust Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would see the end of the Milosevic regime as an objective,''  
Lugar said on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But not all lawmakers favor U.S. involvement in a Balkans civil  
war, let alone military escalation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do not have any national security interests there, and we  
need to get out,'' Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., said on CNN's ``Late 
Edition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has refused to arm the Kosovo Liberation  
Army, which has been fighting Yugoslav forces for independence 
since early last year. Still, every NATO strike on Serb tanks and 
artillery bolsters the KLA. 
</P>
<P>
	``There will be a change in balance of forces on the ground,''  
Albright said. 
</P>
<P>
	But that does not mean an independent Kosovo, said Clinton, who  
favors autonomy for the province. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kosovo lacks the resources and infrastructure to thrive on its  
own. Instead, its independence could actually spur more 
instability,'' Clinton wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling Milosevic ``Europe's worst demagogue,'' Clinton said  
NATO hopes that one day Yugoslavia will join democratic Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	``The realization of this vision will require a democratic  
transition in Serbia itself, for the region cannot be secure with a 
belligerent tyrant in its midst,'' the president wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Sunday, Clinton spoke by phone with the leaders of four  
states bordering Yugoslavia: Hungary, a new NATO member, as well as 
Albania, Bulgaria and Romania, which are not in the alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton spoke of NATO's resolve and discussed ways to cooperate  
more closely on refugees and on a more united and democratic 
southern Europe down the road, said David Leavy, spokesman for the 
National Security Council. ``All these states have been quite 
responsible in standing with NATO,'' Leavy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Zivadin Jovanovic, Yugoslavia's foreign minister, called reports  
of Serb atrocities ``mere NATO propaganda'' aimed at justifying 
airstrikes. He denied ill treatment of any group. 
</P>
<P>
	``All citizens in Yugoslavia are safe, free and equal,''  
Jovanovic said on NBC. ``There is no killing, no raping, no 
depriving of anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the military front, the first of 24 Apache attack helicopters  
are arriving early this week in Albania after delays caused by bad 
weather and crowded airfields handling humanitarian missions for 
refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO's commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, is awaiting  
Pentagon approval for an additional 300 U.S. and allied planes, 
which would raise the alliance's total fleet to about 1,000. 
</P>
<P>
	That will require Clinton to call up as many as 33,000 military  
reserves, mostly for refueling and administration duties. Pentagon 
officials expect that order early this week. 
</P>
<P>
	More low-flying A-10 ``tank-killer'' aircraft, which like Apache  
gunships are good at close-in attacks, are expected to be among the 
reinforcements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
