<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 103rd Boston Marathon Is Set to Go </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Moses Tanui is the current king of the Boston  
Marathon and the unofficial mayor of Eldoret, Kenya. 
</P>
<P>
	He will attempt to rule his domain in Boston again Monday in the  
103rd running of the world's most prestigious marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a lot of pressure being the defending champion,''  
said Tanui, also the 1996 winner. ``Everybody is looking at me. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of times I try to relax and not think about the race,  
but it's very difficult because it's on your mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Kenya, the 33-year-old runner is a hero, with a long string  
of successes. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the 1991 10,000-meter world champion and set the world  
best performance for the half-marathon in 1993. He has run on six 
Kenyan teams that won the World Cross Country Championship and run 
on three Kenyan teams that won the World Half-Marathon 
Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	He owns a large farm, surrounded by an enormous park, in the  
residential area of Eldoret. He provides jobs for many on the farm 
and advice and guidance for many young runners who lack financial 
support. 
</P>
<P>
	He founded the Great Rift Valley Cross Country race to develop  
the youngsters. He also joined six-time world cross country 
champion Paul Tergat in producing a running magazine, ``The 
Athlete,'' which gives rare insights into Kenyan athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	When he leaves Kenya for a race, he misses his people.  
</P>
<P>
	``I try not to think about it,'' he said. ``It's like I'm going  
for a fight. I want to finish what I've been training for. It would 
confuse my mind if I think about anything but the race. Winning 
depends on what you have in the head, not how fast you are. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to win three times ... and then four.''  
</P>
<P>
	Tanui will have a lot to think about during the race. If he wins  
again, he becomes the third Kenyan to win three times in 11 years, 
joining Ibrahim Hussein and Cosmas Ndeti, and the ninth consecutive 
Kenyan champion. 
</P>
<P>
	He also will have to think about the flock of first-class  
runners in the field of 12,775, the largest at Boston except for 
the race's centennial year in 1996, when there were 38,708, the 
most in the history of the sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Included in the field will be Kenyans John Kagwe, winner of the  
past two New York City Marathons; Joseph Chebet, the runner-up to 
Kagwe at New York in 1997 and 1998 and second to Tanui last year; 
Joseph Kamau, the 1997 Boston runner-up; and Sammy Korir, winner of 
the past two Amsterdam Marathons. 
</P>
<P>
	The other contenders include Mexicans Andres Espinosa, the  
fastest man in the field at 2 hours, 7 minutes, 19 seconds, and 
Isaac Garcia. There's also Brazil's Vanderlei Lima and Spain's Jose 
Garcia. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's field is distinguished as well, led by two-time  
defending champion and 1996 Olympic gold medalist Fatuma Roba. 
</P>
<P>
	Also running will be NYC Marathon champions Franca Fiacconi of  
Italy, Anuta Catuna of Romania and Franziska Rochat-Moser of 
Switzerland; two-time Olympic medalist Yuko Arimori of Japan; 1998 
Boston runner-up Renata Paradowska of Poland; and first-time 
marathoners Lynn Jennings of Newmarket, N.H., and Catherine Ndereba 
of Kenya, both having achieved great success at shorter distances. 
</P>
<P>
	Another victory by the smooth-striding Roba would enable her to  
join Germany's Uta Pippig as the only three-time winners since 
women were officially allowed to compete in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Tanui, Roba is highly respected in her country.  
</P>
<P>
	``Children ... they want to be like me,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Surprisingly, Roba prefers the undulating Boston course to  
flatter terrain and thinks she can break the world record of 
2:20:47 by Kenya's Tegla Loroupe. 
</P>
<P>
	Roba is certain to be cheered loudly by the crowd, many from a  
large Ethiopian community in Boston. But the strongest support 
probably will be for Jennings, who has run in the area on numerous 
occasions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Boston crowd is very egalitarian,'' Jennings said. ``They  
will cheer for the people who've been there before. I have a lot of 
friends here, so I should hear a lot of cheering along the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``I intend to use it to help me. It won't be a burden, it will  
be a plus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jennings will need lots of support.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm the babe in the woods,'' she said. ``I'm running against  
people who have run lots of marathons ... the creme de la creme of 
women marathoners.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another big crowd favorite will be Bill Rodgers.  
</P>
<P>
	Rodgers, 51, has won at Boston and New York four times each, and  
will be aiming to break the over-50 course record of 2:31:34 for an 
American. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to be a little younger so I could run well  
against all those Kenyans,'' Rodgers said. ``They have the most 
professional distance runners in the world.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
