<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Temperatures dipped to record lows from Texas to the Carolinas  
on Sunday, dropping nearly to the freezing point in places. Only 
light showers were scattered across other sections of the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Even northern Florida briefly flirted with frost, with a record  
low of 32 at Tallahassee, the National Weather Service said. 
Temperatures there earlier this month had been well above normal 
with highs in the 80s and 90s. The city's previous record was 37 
degrees in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures also hit record lows for April 18 in parts of  
Oklahoma, Texas, Louisiana, Arkansas, Mississippi, and North and 
South Carolina, the weather service said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those records included 34 at McAlester, Okla.; 33 at Meridian,  
Miss.; 35 at Austin, Texas, and 42 at Houston. New Orleans tied its 
record at 43. 
</P>
<P>
	South of the cold air mass, a few showers moved across southern  
Florida, not enough to quench the state's grass and brush fires. 
</P>
<P>
	Farther north, a few light showers were scattered across the  
Great Lakes and into New England during the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavier showers and a few thunderstorms developed across  
northern Indiana and Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Northwest, light showers moved across sections of  
Washington and western Oregon. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, isolated light showers developed in parts of eastern  
North Dakota and northwestern Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a  
morning low of 19 at Gallup, N.M., to an early afternoon reading of 
80 at Yuma, Ariz. 
</P>
</TEXT>
