<HEADLINE> Single Empire Wins Capistrano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Single Empire defeated Le Paillard by 1 1/4  
lengths to win today's $400,000 San Juan Capistrano Invitational 
Handicap, giving trainer Neil Drysdale a 1-2 finish in North 
America's longest Grade I turf race. 
</P>
<P>
	Ridden by Kent Desormeaux, Single Empire covered 1 3/4 miles in  
2:45 4-5 and paid $5.80, $3.20 and $4.40 as the 9-5 wagering 
favorite. Single Empire, an Irish bred and co-high weight of 118 
pounds, took the lead at the head of the stretch over stablemate Le 
Paillard. 
</P>
<P>
	Le Paillard, another Irish bred, returned $5.20 and $4.40, while  
Lucayan Indian, yet another Irish bred, was another 4 1/2 lengths back 
in third and paid $8.40 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	``What a marathoner,'' Desormeaux said. ``He's a two-miler, a  
true marathon horse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drysdale had never won the San Juan Capistrano, although he was  
an assistant to Charlie Whittingham when the Hall of Fame trainer 
saddled the 1-2 finishers in 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory, worth $240,000, increased Single Empire's career  
earnings to $824,113, with five wins in 15 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	In the $109,400 La Cienegas Handicap for fillies and mares,  
Desert Lady caught Hula Queen at the wire to win by a head under 
Corey Nakatani and 117 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Desert Lady covered 6 1/2 furlongs in 1:13 2-5 and paid $4.20,  
$2.80 and $2.20. The victory, worth $65,640, increased her career 
earnings to $219,541. 
</P>
</TEXT>
