<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 N.Y. Winners Take Aim at Boston </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The winners of the last three New York City  
Marathons were strong contenders to capture the women's title in 
today's Boston Marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	But something else connects Italy's Franca Fiacconi, Romania's  
Anuta Catuna and Switzerland's Franziska Rochat-Moser. All three, 
without hesitation, said Fatuma Roba would be the toughest to beat. 
</P>
<P>
	Roba was favored to win her third straight Boston Marathon. Her  
time of 2 hours, 23 minutes, 21 seconds last year was the third 
fastest on the course by a woman. 
</P>
<P>
	The top-flight women's field was led by Roba of Ethiopia, the  
1996 Olympic gold medalist, and included Lynn Jennings, the top 
American woman distance runner who was making her official marathon 
debut. 
</P>
<P>
	But she wasn't expected to beat Roba.  
</P>
<P>
	``The 'Big Woman' is Fatuma,'' Catuna said. ``I think we'll stay  
together (in the race). I think I can win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Catuna won the New York City Marathon in 1996, when she overtook  
Tegla Laroupe -- who set the women's world mark of 2:20:47 at 
Rotterdam last year -- and finished in 2:28:28. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the year, Catuna trains in Boulder, Colo., where the  
roads are wide, the air is clean and the hills are abundant and 
prepare her for Boston's hilly course. 
</P>
<P>
	More than any other race, the 30-year-old Romanian said she  
enjoys running the Boston Marathon, citing its history and the 
competitiveness of its contestants -- particularly the strength of 
the women's field. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone wants to run the Boston Marathon,'' Catuna said.  
</P>
<P>
	Plus, she said, Boston is not as difficult as the New York City  
Marathon because New York has more hills. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boston is easy,'' said Catuna, who placed third in Boston last  
year in 2:27:34. ``It has only four hills. In New York, they have 
plenty. Every two kilometers, there is (another) hill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rochat-Moser disagreed and said both courses are challenging  
with little difference between them. 
</P>
<P>
	``New York and Boston are very hard,'' she said. ``I don't see a  
lot of differences, they are both very hilly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Catuna and Fiacconi, who focus much of their training for  
Boston on hill workouts, Rochat-Moser works on her quick pace. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to have speed, the hills will come on their own,''  
said the 32-year-old who has been running long distances since she 
was just 10. ``I think the race will go very fast. There are a lot 
of good women here, fast women,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rochat-Moser, who trains in Lausanne, Switzerland, also  
incorporates cycling workouts into her marathon training. She said 
she runs about 100 miles a week. 
</P>
<P>
	Fiacconi won New York last year in her personal best of 2:25:17  
and has not raced in any other marathons since. In 1997, she ran 
three marathons in 60 days. She placed third at New York, 13th at 
the World Championships in Athens, Greece, and second in Italy's 
Capri Marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	Since winning New York, the 5-foot-8 Fiacconi -- who towers over  
most of her competitors -- has spent much of her time on interviews, 
traveling and training. For the past two months, she has trained at 
her favorite spot, Rocca Canterano, a hilly area outside of Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter how fast the competition runs, Rochat-Moser believed  
Roba would be wearing the laurel wreath after the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's the Olympian,'' Rochat-Moser said. ``She runs very fast,  
and if she's in good shape, nobody can beat her.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990418.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 09:12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Architect Preaches Less Is More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Architect Sarah Susanka has a few catch  
phrases that leave little doubt of what she thinks about the 
4,000-square-foot homes many families are building. 
</P>
<P>
	She calls them ``starter castles'' and ``Sheetrock barns.''  
</P>
<P>
	Susanka has taken a sabbatical from her Minneapolis architecture  
firm to spread her message that today's smaller families don't need 
homes with grand foyers and master baths the size of some bedrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	She hopes to repopularize residential architecture, which waned  
in this country after the 1920s, and promote building ``not so 
big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The philosophy is on view in her own not-so-big house, which she  
designed and had built several years ago on a bluff above the 
Mississippi River. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-story, 2,400-square-foot walkout where she lives with  
her architect husband, James Larson, and two cats is cottage in 
scale with Oriental details. 
</P>
<P>
	It combines her native English penchant for window box seats and  
other nooks and crannies with an openness that makes the home seem 
bigger than it is. With three bedrooms and 2 1/2 baths, there's room 
for Larson's two adult children and grandchildren to visit. 
</P>
<P>
	The living, dining and kitchen functions are combined in a  
single space used for both formal and informal purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not for everybody,'' she acknowledged on a tour of her  
home. ``There are some people who still love to entertain formally. 
And if you do, I don't want to talk you out of your dining room.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But too many people, Susanka maintains, use their dining rooms  
as a mail-sorting center. She created niches for that purpose near 
the front door by a half-bath and closet. The same area serves as a 
mudroom. 
</P>
<P>
	For people who need an acoustically separate room for a piano or  
some special pursuit, Susanka advocates an ``away'' room. This 
particular home plan can be modified for an older couple by 
converting a screen porch on the main floor into a bedroom or, for 
a family with children, by turning an extra large walk-in closet 
off the upstairs master bedroom into a third bedroom or nursery. 
</P>
<P>
	Although her own home is contemporary Prairie School, Susanka  
and her firm design homes of all styles with the not-so-big 
concept. 
</P>
<P>
	While Susanka's ideas are not unique, others in the field give  
her credit for making them work together and articulating them well 
in her book, ``The Not So Big House,'' which was published in 
mid-October by Taunton Press. It was Amazon.com's best-selling home 
design book last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The book tells readers to build only rooms that they use every  
day and save their money for wood floors, built-ins and other 
design details to give their homes character. 
</P>
<P>
	``What she is doing is starting to showcase a prevailing trend,  
that we're no longer building ego houses but jewel houses,'' said 
Jerry Gloss, a Boulder, Colo., architect and a member of the design 
committee of the National Association of Home Builders. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ten years ago we were doing the Texas two-story entry. We felt  
like we were building Tara,'' Gloss said. Susanka's book is a good 
summary and could wind up as a ``bible'' of the scaled-down 
movement, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard McLaughlin, president of a Minneapolis planning and  
design firm, said Susanka's work is important because she can 
create small, intimate spaces within a home set on a narrower lot 
in a higher density development. 
</P>
<P>
	Susanka didn't begin her career designing homes and initially  
turned down requests to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was sending them off to friends, who I knew would either  
moonlight them in the evenings or had started their own business. 
One day I was standing there and I was about to give my same 
friend's name out, and I thought `You know what? I could be doing 
this,''' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after that residential project, she went into  
partnership in 1983 with Dale Mulfinger, a faculty member at the 
University of Minnesota where she earned her master's degree in 
architecture. 
</P>
<P>
	Susanka estimates the homes being designed by her firm,  
Mulfinger, Susanka, Mahady &AMP; Partners, start at about $230,000 to 
build and have an average cost of around $350,000. Her firm also 
handles smaller projects, such as additions and kitchen redos. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there's a lot of frustrated builders out there who  
want to do better-designed, better-looking, better-quality work but 
the mechanisms in our culture right now force everybody to go for 
lowest dollar per square foot,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, she maintains that most people are looking for  
character, not square footage. She believes better-designed houses 
will last longer and retain their value even though they may lack 
some currently standard features, such as formal dining rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	Susanka wants to convince the middle class that there are  
architects who are affordable, will listen to clients' wishes and 
help them decide what they really want in a home. 
</P>
<P>
	Sara and Harley Weyer worked with Susanka on their modern  
3,200-square-foot Craftsman-style home in Perry, Iowa, and 
pronounced it a great experience. 
</P>
<P>
	The Weyers, who would not disclose the cost of their home, said  
much of the square footage is devoted to a large storeroom on the 
walkout lower level. The rest of the house has a decidedly 
not-so-big feel, which they described as ``cozy, yet good for 
entertaining.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though the dining and living room spaces are really one  
medium-size room, exposed beams delineate the areas. The kitchen 
cabinets are maple with cherry accents, every window is trimmed in 
wood and the staircase is maple and cherry. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was an absolute delight,'' Mrs. Weyer said.  
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The book's Web address is www.notsobighouse.com.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
