<DOCNO> APW19990418.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 23:23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penn FB Latest `Mr. Irrelevant' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- With the Chicago Bears picking last,  
Penn fullback Jim Finn made the perfect ``Mr. Irrelevant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After all, how many other teams are coached by a fellow Ivy  
Leaguer? And what other team has a chairman emeritus who went to 
Penn? Heck, how many other teams even have a chairman emeritus? 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to get the last pick in the draft, and get a guy  
from the Ivy League, and find him at the place to draft him,'' Mark 
Hatley, the Chicago Bears' vice president of player personnel, said 
with a laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was the toughest thing for us to do in the draft, but  
it's sort of funny how things fall out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For the last few years, the last pick in the draft has  
affectionately been dubbed, ``Mr. Irrelevant.'' And despite the 
name, it's not a bad gig. For being the last pick -- No. 253, for 
future trivia -- Finn gets a trip to Disneyland, a parade and a few 
other goodies. 
</P>
<P>
	Not to mention a shot at Chicago's roster.  
</P>
<P>
	``Now I'm going to go to camp and prove I'm not `Mr.  
Irrelevant,''' Finn said. 
</P>
<P>
	The last pick of the draft was supposed to go the expansion  
Cleveland Browns, but they traded it to the Bears. Chicago was 
looking for a fullback throughout the draft, and when the last pick 
rolled around, there was Finn. 
</P>
<P>
	Finn is fourth on Penn's career list with 2,277 yards rushing  
and fifth with 180 points scored. He's also been used as a 
third-down receiver, and at 255 pounds the Bears think he'll be a 
good blocker. 
</P>
<P>
	And with Finn's intangibles, the Bears just couldn't miss. Coach  
Dick Jauron is also an Ivy Leaguer, though he went to Yale. Ed 
McCaskey, the Bears' chairman emeritus, also went to Penn, Hatley 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was one of those things that all fell in place,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
