<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-18 15:13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salvage Team Delays Capsule Search </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Hampered by a bad power switch  
aboard ship, an underwater salvage team on Sunday put off by one 
day its search for Gus Grissom's sunken space capsule. 
</P>
<P>
	The salvage experts will now set sail from Port Canaveral on  
Monday, after they have replaced a switch in a hydraulic power 
unit, said Karen Siebert, a spokeswoman for the Kansas Cosmosphere 
and Space Center. The cosmosphere will restore the 38-year-old 
Mercury capsule if it's recovered from the Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	Siebert said the expedition had to be delayed because there was  
nowhere to buy the needed part on a Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The leader of the expedition, Curt Newport, has teamed up with  
the Discovery Channel to find Liberty Bell 7, which sank following 
Grissom's successful 15-minute suborbital flight on July 21, 1961. 
The hatch blew open prematurely, and the capsule took on so much 
water it could not be lifted by helicopter. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport believes the capsule is on the ocean floor 300 miles  
southeast of Cape Canaveral. He'll use the latest in side-scan 
sonar to try to find it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
