<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Intensifies Serb Strikes  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO today launched its most active  
day of airstrikes in its assault on Yugoslavia, pummeling 
refineries, bridges and dozens of other targets in what it claimed 
were ``highly successful'' operations. But the refugee crisis 
deepened with ethnic Albanians streaming out of Kosovo at the rate 
of a thousand an hour. A car carrying a family across the border to 
Albania struck a land mine planted by Serb forces, killing five 
people. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S.: Kosovo Dead May Total 100,000  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As many as 100,000 young ethnic Albanian men  
may have been killed by Serb ethnic cleansing of Kosovo, the U.S. 
ambassador for war crimes said today. David Scheffer also said 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic ``certainly (is) a prime 
target for investigation'' as a war criminal. Milosevic has been 
advised of that in a letter from prosecutor Louise Arbour of the 
U.N. war crimes tribunal in the Netherlands. Scheffer, appearing on 
Fox News, brought side-by-side NATO photographs of the town of 
Izbica that depicted an area taken at different times. In one 
photo, up to 150 graves appeared where nothing existed before. 

</P>
<P>
	Fire Burns in Florida Everglades  
</P>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- A raging fire burned out of control  
today in the Everglades, torching 70,000 acres of dry marsh grass. 
The fire came within 100 yards of Interstate 75, closing the main 
coast-to-coast route across south Florida known as Alligator Alley. 
Smoke from the blaze has blown as far as Miami, 45 miles away. 

</P>
<P>
	Fuel Cell Vehicle Being Developed  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler AG and Ford Motor Co. are  
partnering with oil companies, a fuel cell company and the state of 
California to develop a demonstration fleet of environmentally 
friendly vehicles, The Toronto Globe and Mail reported. The deal 
will be announced Tuesday on the steps of the Capitol building in 
Sacramento, Calif. The long-range electric vehicles will rely on 
low-grade gasoline instead of batteries. Fuel cells will produce 
electricity using a chemical reaction between hydrogen and oxygen 
and produce little or no emissions. 

</P>
<P>
	Ecevit's Party Leads in Turkey Vote  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's secular  
party was leading Turkish elections today while an ultra-rightist 
group appeared to be making gains. The Islamic Virtue Party, the 
largest party now in parliament, saw a major decline in votes. With 
50 percent of the vote counted, Ecevit's Democratic Left Party had 
23 percent of the vote. Virtue was taking only 16 percent of the 
vote, a sharp decline from the 21 percent that its predecessor, the 
Welfare Party. 

</P>
<P>
	Water Polo Team Stripping for Funds  
</P>
<P>
	MEDELLIN, Colombia (AP) -- Colombia's national water polo team is  
promising ``The Full Monty'' in a one-time-only striptease show to 
raise enough money to reach the world championships in Essen, 
Germany. The team hopes to earn $32,000 at next Thursday's show at 
a disco. Only women will be admitted, at $12 a ticket. The idea, 
which came from a team member's girlfriend, was inspired by the 
1997 British movie about male strippers in unemployment-stricken 
Sheffield, England. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Mixed Early  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average was down in early trading  
on first 30 minutes of trading on Monday. It lost 55.71 points to 
16,795.87 in the first 30 minutes of trading. The dip follows a 
124.50-point gain on Friday. 

</P>
<P>
	Gretzky Ends Career; Rangers Lose  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Wayne Gretzky, the greatest NHL player ever, was  
on the bench in his final game when Jaromir Jagr's goal slid into 
the net, giving the Pittsburgh Penguins a 2-1 overtime victory 
against the New York Rangers. Gretzky, however, assisted on a goal 
for his 2,857th point in his 1,487th game. 

</P>
<P>
	Jazz Beat Timberwolves 97-76  
</P>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The Utah Jazz spoiled Kevin Garnett's return  
to the Minnesota lineup Sunday night, jumping on the Timberwolves 
early en route to their 11th straight victory, 97-76. John Stockton 
scored six points in the game's first eight minutes as the Jazz 
took control early and never let up. Utah built a 19-8 lead with 
3:30 left in the first quarter and held a double-digit lead the 
rest of the game. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  


</P>
</TEXT>
