<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> O's Ripken Sits Out With Back Pain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Cal Ripken missed his fourth game of the season  
on Sunday and will head to Cleveland to have his back examined by a 
doctor. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very disappointing,'' he said before the Baltimore  
Orioles played the Toronto Blue Jays. ``I thought I had turned the 
corner. I felt very good coming in. I told the trainer that I 
thought it was behind me, that I had the capacity to work and do 
the things necessary to play, make strides and get better. But 
that's kind of changed right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, first baseman Will Clark fractured his left thumb on  
an infield grounder Sunday. He returned to Baltimore after the 
game, and it's not known how long he will be sidelined. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, 38, is hitting just .179 (5-for-28) with two RBIs and  
has made five errors -- three short of his 1998 total. 
</P>
<P>
	He left the April 5 season opener in the third inning because of  
back stiffness, then sat out on April 7-8, the first time he missed 
consecutive games since he was a 22-year-old rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	After he made a double error that led to five unearned runs by  
the New York Yankees on Thursday night, he said his back felt fine 
but manager Ray Miller gave him a day off Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken said he felt something in his back during Saturday's game  
but remained in. The pain was worse Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to rationalize it by saying it might be an aching pain  
from playing on turf,'' Ripken said. ``I said let's not evaluate it 
too critically now, let's wait till tomorrow morning and see what 
happens. Tomorrow morning came and I realized it was something more 
than just an aching pain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Orioles traveled to Tampa after Sunday's game, Ripken  
went to Cleveland to see Dr. Henry Bohlman on Monday, when the team 
is off. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not having any answers, and not having gone through too much  
of this kind of thing, I don't know what lies ahead,'' Ripken said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if it's something he could play with for the rest of  
season Ripken said: ``I'll have answers to those questions when I 
have answers for my back. All those things will be asked and 
discussed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, in his 18th major league season, set baseball's Ironman  
mark by playing in 2,632 consecutive games before sitting out 
Orioles' final home game last season. He broke the previous record 
of 2,130 set by Lou Gehrig. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to dealing with back pain, Ripken has said it's a  
mental challenge to push forward following the March 25 death of 
his father, Cal Ripken Sr., a former Orioles manager. 
</P>
</TEXT>
