<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio Teen Describes Accused Parents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- The eldest of four children allegedly long  
forbidden from leaving their home has told investigators of other 
harsh treatment by their parents, including being deprived of food 
and water. 
</P>
<P>
	The children -- ages 4, 8, 11 and 17 -- were removed in late  
January from the family's home in suburban Harrison Township after 
the teen, Eddie Sizemore Jr., mailed a letter to his nearby aunt, 
pleading for help. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger children were found to speak to each other in a  
broken, guttural form of English. All are now in the care of 
another aunt. 
</P>
<P>
	Their parents, Edward and Lucinda Sizemore, remain jailed after  
pleading innocent last week to four counts of non-support of a 
dependent, a misdemeanor. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview published Sunday, Sizemore Jr. told the Dayton  
Daily News he was made to sleep on the living room floor in shorts 
under a sheet of plastic in the winter, and that his parents often 
barred him from drinking water and eating food. 
</P>
<P>
	The teen-ager said their father would occasionally allow the  
children outside years ago but eventually stopped. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators say the children show no signs of physical abuse.  
</P>
<P>
	But ``there were certainly things happening that were abusive,''  
said Mary Anne Nelson, a case manager for Montgomery County 
Children's Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Malocu, an attorney representing Edward Sizemore Sr., said  
his client is a hardworking father who strove to support his 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	``He certainly had no intention to hurt or deprive them in any  
way,'' Malocu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
